article.description: Olympian Yolanda Griffith scored 18 points and paced a balanced attack, leading the Sacramento Monarchs to a 73-65 victory over the Seattle Storm on Wednesday night.
article.headline: Olympian Griffith's 18 paces Sacramento
article.linkText: Monarchs reach .500 with win at Seattle
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Seattle Storm coach Anne Donovan didn't want to
get into a half-court game with the Sacramento Monarchs.

But without WNBA MVP Lauren Jackson in the Storm lineup, the
Monarchs dominated the interior en route to a 73-65 win over
Seattle.

Olympian Yolanda Griffith had 18 points and eight rebounds.
Tangela Smith added 14 points for Sacramento, who reached the .500
mark (13-13) for the first time since May 22.

Jackson returned to her native Australia on Wednesday to visit
her seriously ill grandmother. Jackson, the league scoring leader
with a 20.6 average, was also placed on the injured list with a
sprained right foot. She is expected to miss three games.

Sacramento took advantage of the 6-5 center's absence,
outscoring Seattle 38-18 in the paint.

"One of the things our players have bought into is taking good
shots," Sacramento head coach John Whisenant said. "Each one of
them has a different good shot and they have to learn what it is
and be patient until they get it."

Seattle lost at Key Arena for just the second time this season,
snapping a seven-game home winning streak.

Betty Lennox had 19 points and Olympian Sue Bird added 18, but
Seattle's offense struggled, shooting 37 percent. The Storm's
starting frontcourt was outscored 33-14.

"I thought our first half defense was horrendous," Donovan
said. "In the first half we looked rusty; we looked totally out of
sorts defensively."

Bird and Donovan, a U.S. Olympic assistant coach, took the long
way home from Greece on Sunday.

They missed a connecting flight in Denver, were rerouted to
Portland and took a cab to Seattle.

Sacramento led by as many as 11 in the first half, and took a
45-36 halftime lead. The Monarchs extended the lead to 12 midway
through the second half, before Seattle began to chip away.

Bird's 3-point with 1:45 left pulled Seattle to 66-61, but a
jumper from Smith pushed the lead back to seven. Sacramento hit
5-of-6 free throws in the final minute.

Ticha Penicheiro added nine points for Sacramento, which got 22
points from its reserves.
